  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of A then (the value of f \FUNcomp \FUNid{ A } under v0 is equal to the value of f under the value of \FUNid{ A } under v0 and the value of f under the value of \FUNid{ A } under v0 is equal to the value of f under v0 and the value of f under v0 is equal to the value of \FUNid{ B } under the value of f under v0 and the value of \FUNid{ B } under the value of f under v0 is equal to the value of \FUNid{ B } \FUNcomp f under v0))
  f \FUNcomp \FUNid{ A } is equal to f and f is equal to \FUNid{ B } \FUNcomp f
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a class and v1 is a subclass of v0 then \FUNid{ v0 } \FUNrest v1 is equal to \FUNid{ v1 }))
Proof:
  the domain of \FUNid{ A } \FUNrest X is equal to X and X is equal to the domain of \FUNid{ X }
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of X then (the value of \FUNid{ A } \FUNrest X under v0 is equal to the value of \FUNid{ A } under v0 and the value of \FUNid{ A } under v0 is equal to v0 and v0 is equal to the value of \FUNid{ X } under v0))
  \FUNid{ A } \FUNrest X is equal to \FUNid{ X }
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (for all v3, (for all v4, (for all v5, (for all v6, (if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class and v3 is a class and v4 is a map from v0 to v1 and v5 is a map from v1 to v2 and v6 is a map from v2 to v3 then v6 \FUNcomp v5 \FUNcomp v4 is equal to v6 \FUNcomp v5 \FUNcomp v4)))))))
Proof:
  h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f is a map from A to D and h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f is a map from A to D
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of A then the value of h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f under v0 is equal to the value of h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f under v0)
  Proof:
    a is an element of A
    the value of h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f under a is equal to the value of h under the value of g \FUNcomp f under a and the value of h under the value of g \FUNcomp f under a is equal to the value of h under the value of g under the value of f under a and the value of h under the value of g under the value of f under a is equal to the value of h \FUNcomp g under the value of f under a and the value of h \FUNcomp g under the value of f under a is equal to the value of h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f under a
  Qed.
  h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f is equal to h \FUNcomp g \FUNcomp f
Qed.

Definition:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a class and v1 is a class then for all v2, ((v2 is equal to \FUNfunspace{ v0 }{ v1 }) iff (v2 is a class and for all v3, (v3 is an element of v2 iff (v3 is a map from v0 to v1 and v3 is a function and v3 is an object))))))

Definition:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a map then for all v1, ((v1 is a fixed point of v0) iff (v1 is an element of the domain of v0 and the value of v0 under v1 is equal to v1)))

Definition:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a class then for all v1, ((v1 is a subset of v0) iff (v1 is a subclass of v0 and v1 is a set)))

Definition:
  for all v0, (if v0 is a class then for all v1, ((v1 is equal to \SETpow( v0 )) iff (v1 is a class and for all v2, (v2 is an element of v1 iff (v2 is an object and v2 is a subset of v0)))))

Definition:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v0 is a class and v1 is an object and (v2 is a map and v0 is a subclass of the domain of v2) then ((v0 is inductive regarding v1 and v2) iff (v1 is an element of v0 and for all v3, (if v3 is an element of v0 then the value of v2 under v3 is an element of v0))))))

Axiom (Axiom_of_Infinity):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v0 is a class and v1 is an element of v0 and v2 is a map from v0 to v0 then for some v3, (v3 is a subset of v0 and v3 is inductive regarding v1 and v2))))

Theorem:
  \Nat is a set
Proof:
  f is a map and (the domain of f is equal to \Nat) and for all v0, (if v0 is an object then (if v0 is an element of the domain of f then (the value of f under v0 is equal to v0 \NATplus \NATone)))
  f is a map from \Nat to \Nat
  X is a subset of \Nat and X is inductive regarding \NATzero and f
  \NATzero is an element of X and for all v0, (if v0 is an element of X then v0 \NATplus \NATone is an element of X)
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is an element of X)
  \Nat is a subclass of X and X is a subclass of \Nat
  \Nat is equal to X
  \Nat is a set
Qed.

